Brazilian President Michel Temer and US Vice President Mike Pence met in Brasilia to discuss the historic and strong bilateral relations between the two countries. They highlighted the shared values of democracy and individual freedoms. They also discussed the economic ties between Brazil and the US, with trade flows of over $51 billion and significant investments in both directions. The leaders emphasized the need to further deepen cooperation in areas such as space, defense, and public safety. They also addressed the issue of Venezuelan refugees and the ongoing crisis in Venezuela, calling for the restoration of democracy and the improvement of humanitarian conditions. Pence also expressed concern about illegal immigration from Central America and urged countries in the region to address the root causes of the issue.